amilies, co-workers, friends, and neighbors, Laney’s book demonstrates how the histories of German Nazism and Jim Crow in the American South intertwine in narratives about the past. This is a critical reassessment of a singular time that links the Cold War, the Space Race, and the Civil Rights era while addressing important issues of transnational science and technology, and asking Americans to consider their country’s own history of racism when reflecting on the Nazi past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAerospace engineerszAlabamazHuntsvillexHistoryy20th century. 0aAerospace engineerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aEx-NaziszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aGerman AmericanszAlabamazHuntsvillexHistoryy20th century. 0aRocketryvBiographyy20th century. 0aRocketryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030019803440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021345440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300213454423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300213454/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY